russia, Russia, Italy, England). They also give insight into the first large crises within the organization of the Institute and show how high the demand was for places for pupils and for teacher training places, both from Switzerland and from other countries. In addition, staff members who were close to Pestalozzi report in long letters about their experiences with the method in foreign countries.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEducationvBibliography. 0aEducation. 4aNapoleonische Zeit. 4aPestalozzi, Johann Heinrich. 4aPädagogik. 7aEDUCATION / History.2bisacsh  aNapoleonic Era.  aPedagogy.  aPestalozzi, Johann Heinrich.1 aHorlacher, Rebekka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorlacher, Rebekka, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTröhler, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTröhler, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt0 cprintz978311025081740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311025082440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110250824423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110250824/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles